2. Feature Selection

  1. Method: correlation matrix, SalePrice correlation matrix, scatter plots between the most correlated variables
  2. Detect multicollinearity through heatmap of correlation.
In [47]:
#correlation matrix
corrmat = df_train.corr()
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 9))
sns.heatmap(corrmat, vmax=.8, square=True);

From the correlation matrix, we could conclude some highly correlated pairs:
(1) 1stFlrSF--TotalBsmtSF, GarageCars--GarageArea, GarageCars--GarageYrBlt, GarageArea--GarageYrBlt, YearBuilt--YearRemodAdd, YearBuilt--GarageYrBlt, GarageCars--OverallQual, YearRemodAdd--GarageYrBlt, GrLivArea--2ndFlrSF, YearRemodAdd--Fireplaces, TotRmsAbvGrd--GrLivArea
(2) Saleprice--OverallQual, Saleprice--TotalBsmtSF, Saleprice--GrLivArea, Saleprice--FullBath, Saleprice--GarageCars, Saleprice--GarageArea

From the highly correlated pairs, we could know that GarageCars, GarageArea, GarageYrBlt, these three variables are highly correlated, if we put all these three into our final regression model, it may cause multicollinearity. The same analysis for the pair of 1stFlrSF and TotalBsmtSF, since these variables may includes almost same information.

Since we aimed at predicting saleprice, we want to know the variables highly correlated to it.

Saleprice correlation marix

Features selection rule:
(1) if missing data's percent is higher than 0.15, then, delete the feature. But we would not delete them in this step, we should check those features with lots of missing values, why they are missing, what's the reason for missing and then decide whether delete them or not.
(2) GarageX variables have same number of missing data, but we have already choose the variable of GarageCars to include GarageX's varables information.
(3) From the 'data_description.txt' file, we decide to delete the variables of BsmtCond and BsmtQual, since we have already selected the feature of TotalBsmtSF to represent the information of basement.
(4) for MasVnrType and MasVnrArea, the description says it means Masonry veneer type and Masonry veneer area in square feet, respectively. we could first take a look at the data of MasVnrArea and MasVnrType

5. Normal probabilty plot--identify substantive departures from normality.
QQ plot
1.how to plot QQ-plot
2.if skewness, transform to normal distribution -- log transformation,
if there is a significant number of value zero, can't do log transformation-->how to deal?--create binary variable

In [71]:

We could tell that 'SalePrice' is not normal distributed, it has positive skewness, so we are going to do log-transformation.

For the feature of 'TotalBsmtSF' (total square feet basement area)

In [80]:
sns.distplot(df_train['TotalBsmtSF'], fit=norm);
fig = plt.figure()
res = stats.probplot(df_train['TotalBsmtSF'], plot=plt)

Here we got the problem, since the distribution of 'TotalBsmtSF' is positive skewness, so we intend to do log-transformation, however, 'TotalBsmtSF' has a lot of zero values, which couldn't be transformed by log-transformation.

The author of one notes provided the solution: to apply a log transformation here, we'll create a variable that can get the effect of having or not having basement (binary variable). Then, we'll do a log transformation to all the non-zero observations, ignoring those with value zero. This way we can transform data, without losing the effect of having or not basement.

In [81]:
df_train['HasBsmt'] = pd.Series(len(df_train['TotalBsmtSF']), index=df_train.index)
df_train['HasBsmt'] = 0 
df_train.loc[df_train['TotalBsmtSF']>0,'HasBsmt'] = 1
In [82]:
df_train.loc[df_train['HasBsmt']==1,'TotalBsmtSF'] = np.log(df_train['TotalBsmtSF'])
In [83]:
sns.distplot(df_train[df_train['TotalBsmtSF']>0]['TotalBsmtSF'], fit=norm);
fig = plt.figure()
res = stats.probplot(df_train[df_train['TotalBsmtSF']>0]['TotalBsmtSF'], plot=plt)

6.Suggestions
1.From one of the comments: inspect the residuals plots to detect any non-linear relationships-- it comes down to how well we can model this without increasing the variance of the estimate by too much. Except for small data sets, the best-performing predictive models will probably model this nonlinearity with things like regression splines. In practice, this problem can only be decided upon by trying different models (with, in particular, different degree of regularization) to see which model has the lowest mean squared error on withheld data.

use a more formal procedure for feature selection and be very hesitant to throw away any data. if the regression coefficients of the respective variables are unstable, I would see how much worse the model performs (again using withheld data) if I just use one. An even better solution would be to extract the principal components and use those as predictors instead.

I want to stress that multivariate normality of the data is NOT an assumption of regression analysis (which is probably the most natural approach for this problem) . Instead, it assumes that the error terms are normally distributed (i.e., y given X). Again, we need to inspect the residual plot to check this. Similarly, homoscedasticity refers to the conditional distribution of y given X, so again we need to look at the error terms if we want to plot this in two dimensions.

what I usually look for (in addition to whether the dependent variable is asymmetrically distributed) is unexpected patterns in the data e.g., cutoff thresholds that would be hard to detect otherwise, and maybe even indicate problems with the data.
